# Small-Team Workflow — BYO Postgres + pre-push snapshot

> **Project:** {{ .ProjectPrefix }}
> **Generated by:** mtix {{ .Version }}
> **Workflow audience:** 2-10 trusted developers sharing one Postgres
> instance (Supabase, Neon, RDS, or self-hosted). Suitable for small
> startups and OSS team adoption.

> **Trust banner.** BYO PG = trusted team sharing one database. NOT a
> multi-tenant boundary. Anyone with PG write access can read/modify all
> task data. Treat the DSN like a production database credential.

In this workflow Postgres is the canonical source of truth for task data.
The git-tracked `.mtix/tasks.json` becomes a snapshot timeline (a
DR artifact), not the sync mechanism. Each developer's CLI talks
directly to PG; a client-side `pre-push` hook regenerates the snapshot
before each push.

---

## Setup steps

1. **Provision a Postgres instance.** Managed (Supabase, Neon, RDS) or
   self-hosted. Make sure TLS with a trusted CA is enabled. Note the
   host, port, database name.

2. **Create a least-privilege role for mtix.** Run as a PG superuser
   once during provisioning:

   ```sql
   CREATE ROLE mtix_app LOGIN PASSWORD 'set-a-strong-one';
   CREATE DATABASE mtix OWNER mtix_app;
   \c mtix
   GRANT CONNECT ON DATABASE mtix TO mtix_app;
   GRANT USAGE, CREATE ON SCHEMA public TO mtix_app;
   -- mtix_app needs CREATE during initial migration only; revoke after.
   ```

   After `mtix migrate` has run once, drop the schema-level CREATE:

   ```sql
   REVOKE CREATE ON SCHEMA public FROM mtix_app;
   ```

3. **Store the DSN as an environment variable.** Never paste it into a
   tracked yaml. Each developer adds the following to their shell rc:

   ```bash
   export MTIX_PG_DSN="postgresql://mtix_app@db.example.com:5432/mtix?sslmode=verify-full&sslrootcert=/etc/ssl/certs/rds-global-bundle.pem"
   ```

   For local-only secret storage, write the DSN to `.mtix/secrets`
   (mode 0600, gitignored). mtix loads either source.

4. **Initialize the BYO PG store.** From any team machine, once:

   ```bash
   mtix migrate
   ```

   This creates the schema, including the `audit_log` table and the
   triggers that prevent UPDATE/DELETE on it. Concurrent migrations
   are single-flighted via a PG advisory lock.

5. **Install the example pre-push hook on every machine.** From the
   project root:

   ```bash
   cp examples/hooks/pre-push .git/hooks/pre-push
   chmod +x .git/hooks/pre-push
   ```

   The hook calls `mtix snapshot --timeout 30s` in default mode: if PG
   is unreachable it warns and exits 0 (does not block the push). If
   tasks.json changed it stages the diff as a separate snapshot commit.

6. **Verify the loop.** Make a task change via the CLI, push, and
   confirm a `chore(snapshot)` commit lands alongside your change.

